## What the Audit Constraint Does to Your Technical Options

The prohibition on parallel auth systems has eliminated the Strangler Fig pattern for auth entirely. You cannot run old and new auth simultaneously even briefly. That means:

**The cutover is now a hard atomic switch.** Old auth off, new auth on, no overlap. This is the highest-risk event in your entire migration and it needs explicit engineering attention:

- Pre-cutover: comprehensive test suite against new auth covering every token format, session edge case, credential validation path
- Cutover: maintenance window, not a rolling deploy. Pick a low-traffic window. Have database rollback scripts staged and tested.
- Post-cutover: what is your rollback plan if auth fails 20 minutes after switch? You cannot flip back to old auth if it's been decommissioned. You need old auth infrastructure preserved but offline for at least 72 hours post-cutover.

**This also makes the hybrid approach more compelling, not less.** Without a parallel running period to validate the new system under real traffic, you want to minimize the surface area of behavioral change. Greenfield auth means every code path is new and unvalidated by production traffic. Hybrid auth means only the data access layer is new — the business logic, token formats, and validation rules are carried forward from code that has been running in production. Under an atomic cutover with no rollback, "known behavior" is worth more than "clean implementation."

