      "title": "Migration Success Determinant",
      "content": "The single determinant of success in this migration is organizational verification discipline \u2014 the willingness to resolve ground truth about the actual codebase before committing to plans that assume something about it. This conclusion is empirically grounded in the planning conversation itself: the seam analysis was recommended in cycle 2 and remained unexecuted through cycle 9 (7+ cycles). Schema inspection recommended cycle 3, unexecuted through cycle 9. ORM coupling characterization recommended cycle 5, unexecuted through cycle 9. Compliance escalation identified as urgent in cycle 4, unresolved through cycle 9. In every case, the team planned around unknowns rather than resolving them. The pattern is organizational avoidance of uncomfortable ground truth, not technical inability. The answer is not architecturally sophisticated: make it a rule that no implementation decision proceeds on an unverified assumption about the codebase. If a blocking question has been open more than one sprint and the answer is in the code, stop planning and go read the code. All technical problems in this migration \u2014 ORM decoupling, session store entanglement, distributed transactions, PCI audit sequencing \u2014 have known solution patterns. What makes them unsolvable is discovering them after committing to plans that assumed they weren't there. Successful migrations are distinguished by verification discipline, not architectural sophistication.",
